  "diary": "Woke to that perfect early-June light flooding the bedroom—the kind that makes you grateful you live on Madrona. Coffee and toast while the Sound lay flat and calm below. Grabbed greens at QFC, nothing fancy, just the usual Sunday errand run.\n\nSpent the morning painting, trying to capture that exact quality of light I'd just watched. Watercolor's unforgiving but that's what drew me to it today. The brushwork felt looser than usual, less controlled. Around midday I walked down to the park—Lake Union was packed with boats and paddleboards, all that energy and motion while I just stood there quiet. Watched the light bounce off the water.\n\nBack home for lunch, then settled into knitting by the window for hours. Just the needles clicking, my hands moving through the familiar pattern, the afternoon sliding into evening. Made a simple dinner. By the time darkness came, I was still at the window with tea, feeling that deep Sunday peace—the kind that makes you want to hold onto it before Monday crowds back in.",
  "thought_process": "Today was exactly what I needed after a week of managing other people's flights and schedules. Working air traffic control means constant vigilance, constant responsibility—so Sundays like this, where I could move at my own pace without urgency, felt restorative. The weather helped; the forecast promised calm, and I let that external quiet permission me to stay inward. I chose painting this morning because I'd been thinking about that sunrise all week, and knitting this afternoon because repetitive, meditative work helps me transition from work-brain to rest-brain. Staying home the whole day wasn't isolation—it was intentional. The waterfront walk was my one venture out, just enough to feel connected to the city without being consumed by it. I noticed myself drawn repeatedly to windows and light, maybe because control towers are all about sight lines and clarity. By evening, I was genuinely content.",
